{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Good news first: no, you haven't rebuilt sticky-note's problem, and no, redaction doesn't need to wait. Let me untangle the three questions.\n\n## Are git notes branch-specific? (Two layers with different answers)\n\n**Storage/transport: global.** There is exactly one `refs/notes/conversation-ledger` ref holding a flat map of commit-SHA → note-blob for the whole repo. It doesn't live \"on\" any branch, and syncing it moves *everything* — all branches' conversations — as one unit.\n\n**The view: branch-tied.** Because every event is keyed by its anchor commit, and `cledger log` filters anchors by reachability from your current HEAD. Check out a feature branch, you see its conversations; merge it into main, its commits become reachable from main and the conversations follow — automatically, no sync, no machinery. That part of the promise is real and works today.\n\nNow compare with what sticky-note actually suffers from — I read `docs/branch-switching.md`. Its pain is **working-tree state**: git-tracked `.sticky-note/` files that are dirty on every tool call, so `git checkout` refuses to switch branches, requiring a three-layer stash-wrapper defense. Notes have *none* of that: they never appear in status, never block a checkout, never conflict on branch switch. What you inherited instead is a different, much milder cost: **notes are a separate ref that git doesn't transport by default**. That's not sticky-note's disease coming back — it's the standard tradeoff every out-of-tree git metadata system makes (git-bug and git-appraise have the identical property and ship push/pull wrappers for it).\n\n## The transport gap is not the squash-merge issue — but neither blocks redaction\n\nThese are two different problems that both feel like \"propagation,\" so worth separating:\n\n- **Squash-merge** is a *reachability* problem: conversations anchored to commits that the squash discarded, so they vanish from main's *view* even though they're still stored. Fix = re-anchoring.\n- **Transport** is a *sharing* problem: the notes ref doesn't ride `git push`/`git pull`. Fixing re-anchoring won't touch this.\n\nThe transport fix is honestly the smaller of the two, and your instinct (\"hook into git push\") is right:\n\n- **Push side:** a pre-push git hook that runs the sync push. `cledger install` already installs harness hooks; teaching it to install git hooks too (or set `core.hooksPath`) is the same move.\n- **Fetch side:** an added fetch refspec makes every `git fetch`/`pull` pull the notes ref alongside — with one care point: it must land in a staging ref (like sync's `-incoming`) and get merged, never force-overwrite the local ref, or you'd clobber unsynced local notes. Merging lazily at read time handles the no-post-fetch-hook problem.\n\nWith those two, users \"just use their repos as normal\" — turnbridge's teammates get each other's conversations off ordinary pushes and pulls, which is clearly what its product intent wants (it currently says \"sharing is explicit (`cledger sync`)\", which would get amended).\n\n## So what's the sequencing? A now; only E's *placement* waits\n\nAuto-sync actually **raises** the urgency of capture-time redaction rather than lowering it: the moment the ledger travels on every `git push`, the window between \"secret captured\" and \"secret published\" shrinks from weeks to minutes, and A becomes the main line of defense. Meanwhile every day of verbatim capture is accumulating content you'd someday need purge tooling to clean. Delay compounds; nothing about A depends on how transport works.\n\nThe only piece genuinely coupled to the transport decision is **E's invocation UX** — whether the gate lives in an explicit `cledger sync` command or a pre-push hook, and how it prompts when non-interactive. The scan engine and tiers are identical either way; in hook mode the blocking tier just fails the push with a clear message and an `allowlist` command to proceed. And your instinct about E being \"in the way\" gets *better* under auto-sync, not worse: high-precision-only blocking, at push time, on new events only.\n\nMy recommendation: **A + B-harness + D config now, local purge with `cledger redact` now, E's engine now but wire its entry point after the transport decision, transport hooks as their own near-term work item, squash re-anchoring stays where it was on the roadmap.** No drop-everything required — the infra concern is real but it's additive, not foundational.\n\nAlso, since it changes a documented product commitment in *two* repos (cledger's \"explicit sync\" and turnbridge's \"sharing is explicit\"), worth a line in the design doc's open questions now so the intent isn't lost. Want me to make that doc update and then start on A?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"c08f650fedfb44dd1e095b61aa2bd43ed5735597","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","seq":138},"id":"ev1-1ba323d19073b88ef138fa0c7373d20c6c949638c8a79fc3a33534e80e9f9a75","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T02:38:44.018Z","producer":{"session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.2.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"text":"Good news first: no, you haven't rebuilt sticky-note's problem, and no, redaction doesn't need to wait. Let me untangle the three questions.\n\n## Are git notes branch-specific? (Two layers with different answers)\n\n**Storage/transport: global.** There is exactly one `refs/notes/conversation-ledger` ref holding a flat map of commit-SHA → note-blob for the whole repo. It doesn't live \"on\" any branch, a