{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Honest answer: C off-by-default is fine, E off-by-default is the one place I'd push back.\n\n**C off-by-default: not risky.** Its whole value is catching machine-local env secrets, but the `.env`-as-config pattern you described means its false-positive cost lands on exactly the people who didn't opt in. And it's the nondeterministic layer — off-by-default also protects id stability for everyone who never asked for it. Opt-in is the right call, full stop.\n\n**E off-by-default: this is where the risk actually concentrates.** Here's the problem: A only catches prefixed tokens. The secrets that most commonly show up in real coding-agent transcripts — connection strings, `password:` lines in config files the agent cat'd, bearer tokens in curl output, AWS *secret* keys (the 40-char base64 half has no prefix; only the `AKIA` half does) — are precisely what A structurally cannot catch. E is the only layer standing between those and the remote. With E off, the default-config user who runs `cledger sync` after three weeks of sessions pushes all of it, silently, and by the time anyone notices you're in post-push-purge territory — the expensive case the whole design exists to avoid.\n\nTwo things about the friction worry, though:\n\n1. **Sync is already a rare, deliberate moment.** E isn't per-turn interference; it's one check at a point where the user has explicitly decided to share. Friction there is cheap compared to friction anywhere else in the system.\n2. **Friction is really a function of false-positive rate, not of scanning per se.** A scan that almost never fires isn't \"in the way.\"\n\nSo the compromise I'd propose: **E's scan is default-on, but tiered.** The default profile runs only medium-to-high-precision rules — A's ruleset re-run (catches events captured before A existed or under older rules), keyword-anchored patterns (`password=`, `-----BEGIN`), connection-string shapes. Those block with an interactive prompt and an easy allowlist. The genuinely noisy stuff — entropy heuristics — lives behind an opt-in `--paranoid`/config flag. Result: the typical user hits E rarely and only when it's probably right, and turning it fully off (`sync --no-scan` or config) remains available for people who've made that choice deliberately. That keeps \"sharing is a deliberate user choice\" intact — silently pushing secrets isn't a choice anyone made.\n\n**On purge timing:** split it. The **pre-push local purge** (rewrite the note line, squash the local notes ref) should be built now — it's small, and `cledger redact` is incoherent without it, since a redaction that leaves the old blob reachable in the notes history you're about to push removes nothing. The **post-push purge** (force-push the notes ref, collaborator re-fetch coordination) can be deferred; it's mostly a documented recipe plus a helper command, and nothing else depends on it.\n\nSo my proposed matrix: A default-on · B test-harness only · C opt-in · D available via config (inherently opt-in) · E default-on with a conservative profile, noisy rules and full opt-out available · local purge now, remote purge deferred. Want me to write this into the design doc before we start on A?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"c08f650fedfb44dd1e095b61aa2bd43ed5735597","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","seq":90},"id":"ev1-820f61672cffaa6db7fbbc508da84610816136f70840379f106146050d22b64b","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T02:20:30.069Z","producer":{"session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.2.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":