ord is honest about its own incompleteness, which fits the \"don't silently rewrite history\" commitment better than a bare placeholder does.\n\nWant me to spec this out in the technical design doc, or start prototyping the conservative ruleset first?","type":"text"}],"diagnostics":null,"id":"msg_011CdCURdTmEsTr2V3diDSH3","model":"claude-fable-5","role":"assistant","stop_details":null,"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"type":"message","usage":{"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7612,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"cache_creation_input_tokens":7612,"cache_read_input_tokens":24699,"inference_geo":"not_available","input_tokens":2,"iterations":[{"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7612,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"cache_creation_input_tokens":7612,"cache_read_input_tokens":24699,"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":5338,"type":"message"}],"output_tokens":5338,"server_tool_use":{"web_fetch_requests":0,"web_search_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","speed":"standard"}},"parentUuid":"d0d1c32e-b7b0-4dd0-9c91-a9cc510c62a4","requestId":"req_011CdCURbgcAwKZ8X9msWdAS","sessionId":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","slug":"giggly-dreaming-cookie","timestamp":"2026-07-20T01:53:59.936Z","type":"assistant","userType":"external","uuid":"5f899a8c-3999-44d4-a6bf-f919d08764dd","version":"2.1.215"},"format":"claude-code-jsonl/1"},"recorded_at":"2026-07-20T02:09:59.268Z","schema":"conversation-ledger/v1"}
{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"It's live in this repo — our conversation right now is being captured into it. Here's the mental model:\n\n## How git notes work\n\nA notes ref is just an ordinary git ref (`refs/notes/conversation-ledger`) pointing at a commit chain, like a hidden branch. Its tree is a mapping from **commit SHA → text blob**: \"attach this blob of text to that commit.\" The commits themselves are untouched — a note is metadata *about* a commit, stored alongside it. In this repo right now:\n\n- Both commits (`1f7b031` and `c08f650`) have a note attached. The note on `c08f650` is 46 JSONL lines — one event per line, and the first one visible is literally my `Read` of the design doc from earlier in this conversation.\n- Every `cledger` append creates a new commit on the notes ref (that's the `git log refs/notes/conversation-ledger` history you see — 8+ \"Notes added\" commits). This is the \"notes history retains old blobs\" thing from the purge discussion.\n\nTo view them yourself:\n\n```bash\ngit notes --ref conversation-ledger list           # anchor commits that have notes\ngit notes --ref conversation-ledger show HEAD      # raw JSONL on a commit\ngit log --notes=conversation-ledger                # normal log with notes inline\ncledger log                                        # the friendly view\n```\n\nThey're invisible in `git status`, `git log` (without the flag), and your working tree — that's the \"clean working tree\" property.\n\n## Does sync happen on `git push`? **No — and that's the crucial part.**\n\n`git push` only pushes what your refspec names, which by default is branches (`refs/heads/*`). Notes refs are **never pushed or fetched implicitly** — not by `push`, not by `pull`, not by `clone`. The only ways the ledger leaves your machine are `cledger sync` or a manual `git push origin refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\n\nAnd you can see the boundary in this very repo: your local notes ref is at `8447797`, but GitHub's copy is at `50cd72e` — an older commit from whenever you last ran `cledger sync`. Everything captured since then (including this conversation) exists only on your machine until you sync again. Worth being aware: if this repo is public, the next `cledger sync` publishes our transcripts — tool output and all — which is exactly why E sits at that moment and not at `git push` (where we couldn't intervene anyway, since git never sends the ref).\n\n## On the docs point\n\nAgreed, and it slots naturally into the design: a \"Security posture\" section in the README/design doc laying out the dial positions — A's ruleset (on, not configurable off lightly), D path/pattern rules, C env masking (opt-in), E's tiers (default profile / `--paranoid` / `--no-scan`), and the redact + purge story — each with the threat it addresses and the cost of turning it off. I'll fold that in when I write up the redaction section.\n\nSo, updated plan reflecting everything agreed: **A** default-on conservative ruleset · **B** external scanners as CI test oracle only · **C** opt-in env masking · **D** config-driven path/pattern rules · **E** default-on tiered sync scan · local pre-push purge now, remote purge deferred · docs get a security-settings section. Want me to write the design doc section first, or start implementing A with the B-powered test harness alongside?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"c08f650fedfb44dd1e095b61aa2bd43ed5735597","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","seq":106},"id":"ev1-ece2c859e0db7ba958ee02baff86818ee1ec369a021e8280d0a917e78e534525","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T02:27:08.816Z","producer":{"session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.2.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/