{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Product intent\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tTurnbridge lets a developer continue a visible coding conversation in a\n6\tdifferent agent CLI when they choose to switch providers or tools. It retains\n7\tthe full user-visible turn history—messages, tool calls, and tool results—\n8\trather than requiring a last-minute summary from a rate-limited model.\n9\t\n10\tIt serves two users who are often the same person on different days: a solo\n11\tdeveloper hopping CLIs mid-task (rate limits, model choice), and small\n12\tcollaborating groups whose members use *different* CLIs and want to pick up\n13\teach other's conversations. Sharing rides on Conversation Ledger's git-notes\n14\tstorage; each turn is attributed to its human author via the repo's git\n15\tidentity, and listings show only your own (plus unattributed) conversations\n16\tunless you ask for everyone's.\n17\t\n18\t## Behavioral commitments\n19\t\n20\t- Capture every available visible turn incrementally, not only on clean exit\n21\t  (delivered by Conversation Ledger's hooks; see division below).\n22\t- Preserve source content faithfully and label its originating CLI.\n23\t- Offer one resume picker across supported CLIs while making the session type\n24\t  honest: native resume for same-CLI records, native-format fabrication for\n25\t  cross-CLI records, transcript rehydration as the always-available fallback.\n26\t- Prefer conversations whose repository and code state match the current work;\n27\t  warn rather than silently treating mismatched history as current.\n28\t- Never claim to transfer hidden reasoning, private provider state, or an\n29\t  exact native session; a fabricated session is labeled as imported.\n30\t- Put the developer in control of capture, sharing, and deletion. Sharing is\n31\t  explicit (`cledger sync`); listings default to the current user's records.\n32\t\n33\t## Non-goals\n34\t\n35\t- A team presence system, task tracker, 